export const CHEAT_SHEET = "Being \n Character, Values, and Principles. \n E ducation is rooted in relationships. You cannot teach that which is inanimate. The teacher is critical to the student. So much so, that the student should always have a teacher. The responsibility of finding and having the provision of a perpetual teacher could be likened to the never-ending trail in Alice in Wonderland. Thus, intermittent and iterative mentorship is viable and achievable. \n The student needs to: 1) know holistic fundamentals, 2) Know how they learn best, 3) Know how to select a mentor for the need, 4) be open to life providing the teacher. \n The student teacher relationship is sacred. A teacher provides a curriculum. Life does as well. \n The existential disciplines such as philosophy, religion, and economics are universal for a reason. \n Character in its existential sense is knowing what makes you alive. \n Students understanding their own values helps them to sort out their virtue and vice on their journey towards actualization. \n Principles ground and guide the conscious learner in times of uncertainty as the gaps of instruction are inevitable. \n “The only true wisdom is in knowing you know nothing.”  ―  Socrates \n Being \n Educational \n Spiritual \n Social \n Vocational \n Cultural \n Health \n Financial \n Competency \n Independence \n Curiosity \n Inspiration \n Open mindedness \n Tolerance \n Purpose \n Meaning \n Narrative \n Connectedness \n Wisdom \n Trust \n Hope \n Aspiration \n Identity \n Resilience \n Humility \n Creativity \n Fulfillment \n Understanding \n Reflective \n Realistic \n Potential \n Vision \n Judgement \n Trust \n Connectedness \n Identity \n Aspiration \n Self Esteem \n Empathy \n Understanding \n Openness \n Fulfillment \n Unity \n Family \n Work Ethic \n Pride \n Drive \n Resourcefulness \n Reliability \n Dedication \n Discipline \n Productivity \n Cooperation \n Integrity \n Responsibility \n Professionalism \n Fulfillment \n Connectedness \n Identity \n Community \n Patriotism \n Bias \n Bigotry \n Gender Roles \n Self care \n\n Sacrifice \n\n Moderation \n\n Balance \n\n Assertiveness \n\n Thriftiness \n\n Resourcefulness \n\n Generosity \n\n Adaptability \n\n Helpfulness \n\n Collaborative \n\n Creativity[ \n\n Knowing \n Change is the only constant. In our technological age, change requires unabated personal adaptability. \n Knowing as substantive reality. \n Focus is What is (essence) and How does (function) \n Try to know the substance of a thing or situation. \n Cut to the chase and get to the heart of a matter. \n Seek to know the elemental aspects of information, situations, and people as well as connections or patterns \n “I did then what I knew how to do. Now that I know better, I do better.”  ―  Maya Angelou \n\n The next critical question worth knowing is how. How leads to action or is derived from the desire to act. \n In most formal or academic settings, how is accomplished by following the directions, protocols, and instructions given to tell us how to do a thing. But, how is not always clear. \n How is something that can be maximized. For example, in any college graduating class roughly 50% of students will not work in the field that they graduated in. Which means that the students that did graduate and get a job in their field of study somehow made the best out of a rather mundane occurrence. Maximizing the how occurs when we identify our own intentions, potential, resources, and possibility. This is done both internally and externally. \n\n Knowing \n Educational \n Spiritual \n Social \n Vocational \n Cultural \n Health \n Financial \n Asking for help \n Self advocate \n Learning Style \n Degree Types \n Post HS options \n\n Well being \n Prayer \n Chanting \n Vices \n Virtues \n Living by Values \n Trust \n Connectedness \n Set boundaries \n Aspiration \n Self Esteem \n\n What is Entry level? \n\n Your own skills \n Purpose exercises \n Personal Mission \n Productivity \n Ethical \n Interview skills \n Connectedness \n Identity \n Community \n Introduce themselves \n Enterprising \n Boundaries \n Self care \n\n Saying “no” \n\n Balance \n\n Exercise \n\n Assertiveness \n\n Coping strategies \n Money management \n\n Skill sets \n\n Market forces \n\n Negotiation \n\n Persuasion \n\n Material Value \n\n Doing \n Character should be exercised here. \n Help the student develop their own sense of planning. \n Take into account both the learner’s intention and the intention of the educator. \n What are the best planning methodologies? \n Development of processes for being consistent and disciplined. \n If we parse the Latin etymology of education, we find the words uplift caution or care. A good education constantly uplifts the concerns of the learner bringing some very real sense of closure. \n “The goal of education is to enable individuals to continue their education.”  ―  John Dewey \n There are seven key domains in which being, knowing, and doing operate or are expressed. Those domains are: education, cultural, health, financial, spiritual, vocational, and social. These domains are immutable as they structure and society. \n If we empower the student in their being, knowing, and doing we can create lifelong learners that in turn help to forge a more productive society. \n The beginning of individualized learning is understanding that we can’t control all the factors that encompass the learner. \n Doing \n Educational \n Spiritual \n Social \n Vocational \n Cultural \n Health \n Financial \n Competency \n Independence \n Skill development \n Purpose \n Meaning \n Narrative \n Wisdom \n Aspiration \n Alignment \n Resilience \n Humility \n Perseverance \n Self confidence \n Self control \n Trust \n Connectedness \n Identity \n Aspiration \n Self Esteem \n\n Work Ethic \n Pride \n Drive \n Resourcefulness \n Reliability \n Dedication \n Discipline \n Productivity \n Cooperation \n Integrity \n Responsibility \n Professionalism \n Set boundaries \n\n Identify barriers \n\n Identify connections \n\n Self care \n\n Well being \n\n Stay on budget \n\n Forecast Earnings \n\n Time management \n\n Resource management \n\n EXAMPLE \n\n EXAMPLE 2\n";

export const EXEMPLAR_ELA_6 = "Lecturer’s name:   \n Date:  \n Course: ELA 6 \n Unit 4: Analyzing and Crafting Argumentative Texts \n Unit Duration: 25 days \n Lesson Duration: 45- 60 minutes \n TEKS: \n 6.6C: Use text evidence to support an appropriate response. \n 6.6I: Reflect on and adjust responses as new evidence is presented. \n Lesson Part # \n\n Topic: Supporting my opinion with evidence \n Lesson objectives:   \n SWBAT cite text evidence to support a response. \n SWBAT adjust response as new evidence is presented. \n Essential Questions:   \n How do I form an opinion? \n Why is it necessary to support my opinion with facts? \n   LYS Methodology \n Be (Character/Values/Principles) - Vocational- Resourcefulness \n Know (What resources are available to the student/ How can they use them) - Social- set boundaries \n Do (Execute with Excellence) - Educational- Skill Development \n Resources (Include Technology): \n Docs Handout: https://docs.google.com/document/d/17nHpkMBoi5F3fsxnS2ervOyyY_AyAx8BFg9vjWxCad8/edit \n Teacher selects a question for students to research and form an opinion on. \n Teachers can pre-select and share resources for student research or outline research parameters/ guidelines for students to determine their own sources. \n Suggested Resource \n Britannica, ProCon: https://www.procon.org/ \n KidzWorld, The Pros and Cons of Homework: https://www.kidzworld.com/article/29686-the-pros-and-cons-of-homework/ \n Junior Scholastic Debates: https://junior.scholastic.com/pages/topics/debate.html?page=1 \n Instructional Input - Asynchronous \n A S: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n Teacher provides a question and students brainstorm reasons both FOR and AGAINST the question. \n If possible, provide a chat board or other area where students can share their ideas and read and respond to the ideas of other students. \n State the purpose: Good writers use facts to support their opinions. Today, we will read and analyze sources in order to gather evidence and present our opinions on this same question. \n M: Modeling (I do) \n Use an article and model for students how to cite text evidence. Include a sentence starter that reveals the source, “According to the Pew Research survey, ___”. Work together to gather one piece of evidence that supports each side of the argument. \n Guide students to record the source information for the modeled text. \n Citation Tutorial found here: https://libguides.bc.edu/citation-tutorial/record \n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n Students work in small groups or individually to continue gathering evidence from the sources. Students correctly cite the information and record source information for 2-4 sources. \n Provide a checklist or clear directions on how students can check that their work and sources are cited correctly. \n Instructional Input - Synchronous \n AS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n Teacher provides a question and students brainstorm reasons both FOR and AGAINST the question. \n Share out and record class responses. Encourage students to add new ideas to their list \n State the purpose: Good writers use facts to support their opinions. Today, we will read and analyze sources in order to gather evidence and present our opinions on this same question. \n M: Modeling (I do) \n Use an article and model for students how to cite text evidence. Include a sentence starter that reveals the source, “According to the Pew Research survey, ___”. Work together to gather one piece of evidence that supports each side of the argument. \n Guide students to record the source information for the modeled text. \n Citation Tutorial found here: https://libguides.bc.edu/citation-tutorial/record \n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n Students work in small groups or individually to continue gathering evidence from the sources. Students correctly cite the information and record source information for 2-4 sources. \n As time permits, discuss evidence and support students in correctly citing evidence by stating the source. \n Independent Practice/ Homework \n Students use the gathered evidence to write a personal opinion that answers the question. A complete answer includes a clearly stated opinion, at least 3 pieces of evidence correctly cited, and clear explanations for each piece of evidence used. \n Lesson Close \n What is the answer to the essential question, and why does it matter to me in terms of:  \n Vocational- Resourcefulness \n Social- set boundaries \n Educational- Skill Development \n\n Being resourceful means looking for information, resources, and support in places that others might not think of. In order to form a clear opinion that is supported by facts, it is necessary to be resourceful. When creating an argument or determining your stance, you should use as many credible sources as you can to help ensure you are fully educated and aware of the topic at hand and how it impacts you and others. This is a skill necessary in both work and life because being able to identify sources of information and use the information you have to make decisions allows you to be creative, productive, and a reliable worker. \n Regardless of the opinion you hold, it is important to know that you have an opinion and that, likely, within that opinion you know there should be certain boundaries set. Consider the arguments that people make both for and against today’s topic and think about what we have learned about Source credibility and logical fallacies. When analyzing the evidence and reasons, are people setting boundaries for themselves or expecting others to set those boundaries. What does that mean for the evidence and reasons used to support one’s opinion? This is important to consider when forming your own opinion and analyzing the opinions of others. What is within a person’s control and how does the amount of control a person has or perceives they have impact someone’s opinion? Additionally, it is your job to set boundaries around what you will and won’t let affect you when it comes to those who disagree with your personal opinion. If someone pushes against you and asks questions, how will you respond? This is the importance of using credible facts, so that you know you have information that you agree with to support your own opinions. \n Education is about developing new skills. Using technology is certainly an important way that we develop new skills. Skill development is about what you actually do. What you read, the questions you ask and listen to the answers, the way you respond to others and present your opinions. Skill development is about taking the facts in front of you and using that information to form new ideas and take new action. So, after you have gathered evidence and formed an opinion, the next question is- what are you going to do about it? Consider today’s question and ask yourself: it is time to look at your school or community policies and determine if they align with the research you have done and the claims you have stated. If they don’t, what can you do about it? You are not too young to take action. It can be argued that you are never too young to take action, so be sure to take your new learning and put it to use by pushing for change or supporting policies already in place. \n\n This is the assignment page (below)!!! \n\n Lesson 9.B \n\n Student Name: Date: \n Teacher Name: Period/Teacher: \n\n : \n\n Course \n Unit \n Content Objective: \n Lesson Objective: \n LYS Methodology \n\n Assignment Instructions: \n\n Essential Questions: \n\n Lesson Close : \n\n Accommodations/Modifications Provided On This Assignment: \n\n Accommodation/Modification \n Applied To This Assignment (Y/N) \n Extra Time \n\n Notes/Presentation Copy Provided \n\n Study Sheet Provided \n\n Graphic Organizer \n\n Mnemonic devices \n\n Larger Size Font \n\n Shortened Text \n\n Peer Support \n\n Preferential Seating \n\n Frequent On Task Reminders \n\n Provided A Completed Example \n\n Visual Organizer Provided\n";

export const EXEMPLAR_ELA_8 = "Lecturer’s name:   \n\n Date:  \n Course: G8 ELAR \n\n Unit: 04 \n Unit Duration: 25 days \n Lesson Duration: 1 -2 days \n TEKS: \n 8.5A \n 8.5B \n 8.5C \n Lesson Part # \n  1 of 4 (use with “Arguments in Writing”, “Comparing Arguments”, and “Analyzing Argumentative Texts”) \n\n Topic: \n  Arguments in Writing \n Lesson objectives:   \n   After the lesson, students will be able to: \n ask and answer their own questions regarding the reading; verify predictions \n analyze characteristics of an argumentative text \n Essential Questions:   \n   What are some characteristics of an argument? How does recognizing the characteristics of an argument help me to succeed? \n   LYS Methodology \n Be (Character/Values/Principles) - Awareness of how rhetoric and emotion can be used in argumentative texts will help you navigate the world while being true to your principles. \n Know (What resources are available to the student/ How can they use them) - When you find yourself wondering whether something is true -or if it is relying too much on the “art” of persuasion-be sure to do your research. You can use the internet, ask peers, and base your thoughts on your past experiences. \n Do (Execute with Excellence) - In any decision we make, we want to be sure that it is the right one. Recognizing argumentative characteristics will help you in daily life. \n\n Resources (Include Technology): \n YouTube video- Rhetoric: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-oUfOh_CgHQ \n Recess Article #1: https://parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/13/students-who-lose-recess-are-the-ones-who-need-it-most/ \n Recess Article #2: https://www.scholastic.com/teachers/articles/teaching-content/recess-makes-kids-smarter/ \n **Any argumentative texts about the same concept will work** \n Instructional Input - Asynchronous \n AS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n Watch the video and think of at least one example of rhetoric that students may have seen. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-oUfOh_CgHQ \n M: Modeling (I do) \n Review key concepts of video \n Explain that although “argumentative” has a negative connotation, it is not always negative. It can be, however, and that is why recognizing this genre is important. \n Go over rhetoric and use of evidence and rebuttals. \n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n Look at the title of article one. What are some predictions? What do you think will be the main idea of this text? What do you think the main purpose may be? \n Teacher input as needed for the first round of predictions. \n Keep a list of questions to answer before, during, and after reading. \n Independent Practice: \n Students will read the first article. https://parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/13/students-who-lose-recess-are-the-ones-who-need-it-most/ \n They will make notes of which predictions were correct and which were not. \n They will list areas of the article that effectively use argument and evidence. \n They will repeat all steps for the second article (including predictions and notes). https://www.scholastic.com/teachers/articles/teaching-content/recess-makes-kids-smarter/ \n In an asynchronous scenario, students will type these notes and turn them in or participate in a discussion board. \n\n Instructional Input - Synchronous \n AS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n Watch the video and think of at least one example of rhetoric that students may have seen. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-oUfOh_CgHQ \n M: Modeling (I do) \n Review key concepts of video \n Explain that although “argumentative” has a negative connotation, it is not always negative. It can be, however, and that is why recognizing this genre is important. \n Go over rhetoric and use of evidence and rebuttals. \n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n Look at the title of article one. What are some predictions? What do you think will be the main idea of this text? What do you think the main purpose may be? \n Teacher input as needed for the first round of predictions. \n Keep a list of questions to answer before, during, and after reading. \n Independent Practice: \n Students will read the first article. https://parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/13/students-who-lose-recess-are-the-ones-who-need-it-most/ \n They will make notes of which predictions were correct and which were not. \n They will list areas of the article that effectively use argument and evidence. \n They will repeat all steps for the second article (including predictions and notes). https://www.scholastic.com/teachers/articles/teaching-content/recess-makes-kids-smarter/ \n Students can discuss in groups if desired. All students will need to hold on to their own notes until the next class as we finish the assignment. \n\n Lesson Close \n\n What is the answer to the essential question, and why does it matter to me in terms of:  \n\n Educational? Learning how to determine whether an argument is valid or not is a valuable educational tool. Correcting or confirming predictions is a skill that will be needed as you continue to learn. \n\n Social? Looking for characteristics with argumentative writing or speeches will help y ou set boundaries and understand where to place trust. \n\n Cultural? These skills will help you identify biases in your culture, work culture, or s ocial circle. \n\n Financial? Understanding how “argumentative appeal” works can help with negotiations. Generating your own questions will help you navigate this. \n\n Health? Anal yzing arguments will help you find balance in being “too trusting” and being “too cynical.” This balance is critical. \n\n Vocational? In any job, you have a responsibility to your employer and customers, as well as to yourself. Understanding how persuasive techniques translate into the real world will help you handle that responsibility. \n\n Spiritual? What ever vision you have of the future, the skills here will help you maintain your personal boundaries.\n";

export const EXEMPLAR_ELA_8_LITERATURE = "Lecturer's name:\n\nDate:\nCourse: G8 ELAR\n\nUnit: 05 (Literature, Short Fiction, Poetry)\nUnit Duration: 25 days\nLesson Duration: 1 day\nTEKS: 8.5A, 8.5C\nLesson Part # 1 of 5\n\nTopic: Establishing purpose and making predictions in text (across genres) using Langston Hughes\n\nLesson objectives:\nAfter the lesson, students will be able to:\n- establish a purpose for reading by beginning to generate questions\n- make predictions before, during, and after reading\n\nEssential Questions:\nWhy is it important to set a purpose for a task?\n\nLYS Methodology\nBe (Character/Values/Principles) — Spiritual; Purpose\nKnow (What resources are available to the student) — Vocational; purpose-driven exercises\nDo (Execute with Excellence) — Social; discussion\n\nResources (Include Technology):\nLangston Hughes / \"Thank you, M'am\" background information. Suggested sites:\n- https://poets.org/poet/langston-hughes\n- http://www.americaslibrary.gov/aa/hughes/aa_hughes_subj.html\n- https://americanliterature.com/author/langston-hughes\nStory access (free, not public domain):\n- https://shortstoryamerica.com/pdf_classics/hughes_thank_you_maam.pdf\nReading-strategy supports:\n- CSR chart for predictions: http://www.adlit.org/strategies/22355/\n- Anticipation journal for generating questions: http://www.adlit.org/strategies/19712/\n- \"First Lines\" prediction list: http://www.adlit.org/strategies/23330/\n\nInstructional Input — Asynchronous (the Synchronous flow follows the same sequence below)\n\nAS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction)\nAsynchronous situations may require a video walkthrough; a discussion board may be helpful.\nAsk students to think of a time they have had to make a prediction — what to wear based on the weather, predicting how someone's mood will be, predicting how a movie will end. Note the \"purpose\" of their prediction as well.\n\nM: Modeling (I do)\nPull up any grade-appropriate text. Set your purpose aloud (e.g., \"I am going to read this article to learn about dog training and I need to make some predictions about what I will learn and need to understand.\").\nGenerate a question that you have and will want to monitor as you read.\nUse the \"first lines\" graphic organizer. Show students how you make predictions based on the first line only of each paragraph.\n\nGP: Guided Practice (We do)\nRepeat the steps from the modeling portion but allow students to work alongside you.\nRead over the background information about Langston Hughes — background will be critical for understanding the story.\nProvide a copy of \"Thank you, M'am\" plus the anticipation and CSR prediction sheets.\nExplain that students will need to form questions before, during, and after reading, and make predictions that they then correct or confirm after reading.\nWork together to establish the purpose for reading. Note: you will not be reading the text during this lesson — you are practicing predicting skills and covering background. Students keep their supplies organized for the duration of this lesson group.\n\nIndependent Practice / Homework\nStudents should:\n- Establish a purpose for reading the short story\n- Begin thinking of questions they may have about Hughes and the story (for the next lesson)\n- Engage in informal discussion about purpose and possible questions/predictions based on what we know so far\n\nLesson Close\nWhat is the answer to the essential question, and why does it matter to me in terms of:\n\nSpiritual? Setting a purpose in even minor tasks keeps you focused on your greater, overall purpose. If you consciously set a structure and meaning for tasks, it will help solidify your holistic spiritual self.\n\nVocational? It is fair to assume that most of what you do at work will have a specific purpose. There won't be many times that your job has no end game whatsoever. By taking steps now to recognize and establish purpose-driven exercises, you are preparing yourself for this in the real world.\n\nSocial? During this lesson — either verbally or via discussion board — you participated in cooperative discussions with your classmates in order to set a purpose and discuss needed information. This cooperation is a crucial social component.\n";

export const EXEMPLAR_MATH_6 = "Lecturer's name: N/A\n\nDate: Day 1\nCourse: Math 6\n\nUnit: Equivalent Forms of Fractions, Decimals, and Percents\nUnit Duration: 10 days\nLesson Duration: 1 day\nTEKS: 6.4E, 6.4F, 6.4G, 6.5B, 6.5C\nLesson Part #1\n\nTopic: Converting Fractions and Decimals to Percentages\n\nLesson objectives:\n1. SWBAT (Students will be able to) define a percent as a fraction (or part-to-whole ratio) with a denominator of 100.\n2. SWBAT find equivalent decimals, fractions, and ratios to percents.\n3. SWBAT model equivalent decimals, fractions, and percents on 10 x 10 grids.\n\nEssential Questions:\nWhat is a percent?\nHow are fractions and decimals converted to percentages?\n\nLYS Methodology\nBe (Character/Values/Principles) — Educational and Financial — How can learning about percentages help you become a responsible individual in regard to your time, finances, and creativity?\nKnow (What resources are available to the student / how can they use them) — Educational and Financial — Why is it important that we know how to calculate percentages from fractions and decimals? And why is this related to the financial umbrella?\nDo (Execute with Excellence) — Educational, Financial, and Vocational — How do we become resourceful? How can we use percents to stay on a budget or forecast earnings?\n\nResources (Include Technology):\n- Simplifying Fractions warm-up: https://www.mathworksheets4kids.com/simplify-fractions.php\n- Fraction–Decimal–Percent practice handout (3 tiered pages: Level 1, Level 2, Level 3)\n- Online quiz for independent practice\n\nInstructional Input — Asynchronous (the Synchronous flow follows the same sequence below)\n\nAS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction)\nStudents warm up for today's lesson by practicing simplifying fractions. This skill will be assessed during this unit.\n\nM: Modeling (I do)\nTeacher reviews how to convert percent to decimal.\n- Steps: When going from percent to decimal, move TWO places to the LEFT.\nTeacher reviews how to convert decimal to percent.\n- Steps: When going from decimal to percent, move TWO places to the RIGHT.\nTeacher reviews how to convert fraction to decimal and percent.\n- When going from fraction to percent: scale the fraction up or down to 100; convert the scaled fraction to a decimal using place value; move the decimal point TWO places to the RIGHT.\n\nGP: Guided Practice (We do)\nTeacher reviews the first 1–2 problems of each section to model how students should complete it.\nUse the tiered Fraction/Decimal/Percent Practice handout — target Level 1, Level 2, and Level 3 (high-achieving) students by providing varied forms of practice and splitting them evenly.\n- This activity becomes intentionally repetitive so students can internalize how to move from one form to the next.\n- Push students to ALWAYS simplify fractions.\n- Some students may be unable to simplify; provide necessary scaffolding for those students.\n\nIndependent Practice / Homework\nStudents complete the practice online after the lesson — Fractions, Decimal, Percent Quiz — and the additional practice page.\n\nLesson Close\nFinancial\n\"Financial freedom is available for those who learn about it and work for it.\" — Robert T. Kiyosaki\n\nThe term \"percent\" means \"out of a hundred.\" In mathematics, percentages are used like fractions and decimals — as ways to describe parts of a whole. When you are using percentages, the whole is considered to be made up of a hundred equal parts. Learning about percentages is another way to learn how to be a responsible individual regarding your time commitment to becoming financially independent. Think about the amount of time, in percent form, that you spend either reading a book, connecting with mentors, or crafting your creativity through different outlets. What percent of time are you spending bettering yourself and others?\n\nYou will see percentages almost everywhere: in shops, on the internet, in advertisements, and in the media. Being able to understand what percentages mean is a key skill that will potentially save you time and money and will also make you more employable. Percentages are important for understanding the financial aspects of everyday life and can help you become resourceful when handling budgets for yourself, a business, or any important financial decisions.\n";

export const EXEMPLAR_SCIENCE_7 = "Lecturer’s name:   \n\n Date:  \n Course: Science 7 \n\n Unit: Organisms and environments \n Unit Duration: 18 days \n Lesson Duration: 1-2 class periods \n TEKS: 7.11A - Examine organisms or their structures such as insects or leaves and use dichotomous keys for identification. \n Lesson Part # 1 of 1 \n\n Topic: Identification using dichotomous keys \n\n Lesson objectives:   \n Understand that dichotomous keys are tools used to classify organisms \n Identify organisms using a dichotomous key \n Essential Questions:   \n How are dichotomous keys used to classify organisms? \n   LYS Methodology \n Be (Character/Values/Principles) - Curiosity: Being curious is an asset. \n Know (What resources are available to the student/ How can they use them) - Options: How do we identify and classify our options? \n Do (Execute with Excellence) - Leverage curiosity to maximize options. \n\n Resources (Include Technology): \n Dicho tomous Key Murder Mystery \n The Crime https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114261 \n Solving The Crime https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114281 \n Dichotomous Keys https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114296 \n Dichotomous Keys: Identification Achievement Unlocked https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wpKulkADzBk&amp;t=29s \n Fish Identification https://fergusonfoundation.org/btw-students/fish-identification/ \n Dichotomous From Top To Bottomous https://www.nps.gov/goga/learn/education/upload/dichotomous.pdf \n Insect Dichotomous Key https://www.insectidentification.org/insect-key.asp \n\n Instructional Input - Asynchronous \n AS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n Students will investigate a murder-mystery that involves weeding out suspects based on characteristics \n The Crime https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114261 \n Solving The Crime https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114281 \n Dichotomous Keys https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114296 \n M: Modeling (I do) \n Introduce students to the word “dichotomous” giving attention to the prefix “di-” which means two \n Recap classification \n Ask students to give examples of classification and its purpose \n\n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n Watch Dichotomous Keys: Identification Achievement Unlocked for examples of using a dichotomous key \n Allow students to practice identifying fish using a dichotomous key using Fish Identification \n\n Instructional Input - Synchronous \n AS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n Students will investigate a murder-mystery that involves weeding out suspects based on characteristics \n The Crime https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114261 \n Solving The Crime https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114281 \n Dichotomous Keys https://www.texasgateway.org/resource/dichotomous-keys-murder-mystery#section-id-114296 \n M: Modeling (I do) \n Introduce students to the word “dichotomous” giving attention to the prefix “di-” which means two \n Recap classification \n Ask students to give examples of classification and its purpose \n\n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n Watch Dichotomous Keys: Identification Achievement Unlocked for examples of using a dichotomous key \n Allow students to practice identifying fish using a dichotomous key using Fish Identification \n\n Independent Practice/ Homework \n Complete tree identification Dichotomous From Top To Bottomous \n Have students find a picture of an insect or assign one that can be identified using Insect Dichotomous Key \n For a challenge, have students create their own dichotomous key from ten images given to them or chosen by teacher. The images must be of organisms that are closely related and can be easily classified based on differing features \n Lesson Close \n\n Dichotomous keys are tools that are used to help classify organisms. They consist of at least two opposing statements that describe characteristics that can be used to sort organisms into groups. \n\n Connection to Education Domain \n When is curiosity an asset? \n Being curious means that you are eager to learn and discover new things. Being a lifelong learner has benefits that extend outside of the classroom. We continue to seek out more knowledge in our personal lives, work roles, and in higher education. Can you think of a situation where being curious is helpful? How can we use curiosity to better ourselves? \n\n How do we discover our options? Why is identifying our options important? \n We can use our innate curiosity to discover the options that we have in life. Without figuring out our options, we won’t know the full extent of our opportunities in life. If we are never presented with what can be, we will always stay where we are. Have you considered the courses you will take next year? Have you considered your options after high school?\n";

