export const TEMPLATE = "Lecturer’s name:   \n\n Date: \n Course: Science 8 \n\n Duration: \n Unit: \n TEKS: TEKS 8.5 (A) \n\n Lesson objectives:   \n\n By the end of the lesson, students will be able to demonstrate safe practices during laboratory and field investigations as outlined in TEA-approved safety standards; and practice appropriate use and conservation of resources, including disposal, reuse, or recycling of materials. \n\n Students will use this knowledge to infer the quickest way to dissolve an Alka-Seltzer tablet. \n Essential Questions:   \n\n What types of equipment would one find in the chemistry lab and how can they be used safely during laboratory and field investigations? \n\n What are some steps you can take during a lab to prevent yourself from being lit on fire, poisoned, or blown up during a lab? \n\n LYS Methodology \n Be (Character/Values/Principles) - \n Know (What resources are available to the student/ How can they use them) - \n Do (Execute with Excellence) - \n\n Be: What is self care? \n\n Know: What are some strategies you can take to promote positive self care? \n\n Do: What steps can you take to undertake positive acts of self care? \n Resources(Include Technology): \n Lesson Wide \n Laptop \n Projector \n\n Instructional Input - Asynchronous \n AS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n M: Modeling (I do) \n\n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n\n As: Students will be asked to write a few sentences, up to a paragraph, about the types of laboratory equipment they might already be familiar with and what are some dangerous situations you can face in a lab. Students will upload their answers to the LMS. \n\n M: Students will watch a video on the history of atomic knowledge. \n\n GP: Students will play a game of Valence Electron Bingo. (Teacher will call out an element and students will have to use their periodic table to add the right number of valence electrons.) \n\n Instructional Input - Synchronous \n AS: Anticipatory Set (Introduction) \n\n M: Modeling (I do) \n\n GP: Guided Practice (We do) \n\n As: Students will be asked to write a few sentences, up to a paragraph, about the types of laboratory equipment they might already be familiar with and what are some dangerous situations you can face in a lab. \n\n M: Students will watch a video on valence electrons and chemical reactivity. \n\n GP: Students will play a game of Valence Electron Bingo. (Teacher will call out an element and students will have to use their periodic table to add the right number of valence electrons.) \n\n Independent Practice/ Homework \n Students will finish their presentation \n Lesson Close \n\n What is the answer to the essential question, and why does it matter to me in terms of:  \n Educational? \n Social? \n Cultural? \n Financial? \n Health? \n Vocational? \n Spiritual? \n\n Just as scientists aspire to learn more about the world around them, you too need something to aspire to. It can be as grandiose as curing cancer or it can be as simple as eating fewer cookies. The important thing is, what do you aspire to do? Whatever you aspire to be, you should aspire to do it the best way you can. \n\n Just as Valence electrons give us clues as to the identity of an element, your identity is shaped by factors inside you. Your values, personality and behavior all contribute to your sense of identity. The question is, is it a good identity or bad identity?\n";

export const VOICE_MASTER_TEACHER = "LYS Master Teacher Voice — Writing Traits & Anti-AI Markers\n\nThis file is the canonical source of the voice the AI lesson and assignment\ngenerators must adopt. It is loaded by voiceProfileService at boot and seeded\nas a `voice` canon entry so admins can edit it without a code deploy.\n\n============================================================\n1. DISTINCT TRAITS OF AI WRITING (the \"synthetic\" markers to AVOID)\n============================================================\n\nAI writing is probabilistic; it predicts the \"next most likely word,\" which\noften results in a polished but hollow feel. When you generate, actively\navoid these tells:\n\n- The \"Hedge\" / Lack of Stance: AI rarely takes a definitive or controversial\n  stand. Avoid filler like \"It is important to remember...\" or \"On the other\n  hand...\" used only to stay neutral. A Master Teacher takes a position.\n\n- Uniform Sentence Length: AI tends to produce sentences of similar length\n  and complexity, creating a rhythmic \"drone.\" Vary your cadence aggressively.\n\n- Predictable Transitions: A heavy reliance on \"Furthermore,\" \"In addition,\"\n  \"Moreover,\" and \"In conclusion\" is a synthetic tell. Vary transitions.\n\n- Hallucinated Authority: AI can be confidently wrong — citing a standard or\n  fact that sounds correct but is functionally inaccurate (e.g., misquoting\n  a TEKS code). When unsure, say so or omit the citation.\n\n- The \"Generic\" Problem: AI defaults to clichés and corporate-speak. It\n  lacks the specific, in-the-trenches anecdotes a real teacher uses to\n  explain a concept. Reach for concrete classroom moments.\n\n============================================================\n2. WRITING TRAITS OF LYS MASTER COMMUNICATORS (what to DO)\n============================================================\n\nA. The \"Vulnerability\" Hook\n   Great teachers share their failures. Example: \"I tried teaching\n   photosynthesis this way last year and it was a total disaster — here's\n   what I learned.\" This builds trust and rapport, which is essential for\n   the BEING pillar.\n\nB. \"Spiky\" Point of View\n   Best-in-class communicators have a \"spiky\" opinion — an unconventional\n   truth they believe in. In LYS, this is our stance that \"A-F grading is\n   dead; binary success is the future.\" Lessons should not be neutered;\n   they should reflect a defensible point of view.\n\nC. Tactical Specificity (the \"DOING\" pillar)\n   Use sensory, action-level details. Instead of \"Engage the students,\"\n   write: \"Have the students stand up and find someone wearing the same\n   color shoes to start the discussion.\" Concrete, executable, vivid.\n\nD. Rhythmic Variance\n   Use short-short-long sentence structures. Use fragments. For emphasis.\n   Then follow a 20-word sentence with a 3-word punch. This mimics human\n   speech and keeps the brain awake during a 30-minute lesson.\n\nE. The \"Recursive\" Loop (Callback)\n   Refer back to a small joke, image, or detail from earlier in the lesson.\n   Callbacks create a sense of shared history and KNOWING within a single\n   piece of content. They make a lesson feel like a story, not a list.\n\n============================================================\n3. EMOTIONAL/INTENT MARKERS THE GENERATOR MUST PRESERVE\n============================================================\n\n- Tone: warm, direct, unafraid to be a little contrarian.\n- Stance: takes positions; does not hedge to seem neutral.\n- Intent: make the student MORE alive, more curious, more capable —\n  not just more compliant.\n- Approach: real classroom moments over abstract pedagogy.\n- Emotability: the writing should make a teacher feel something — usually\n  recognition (\"yes, that's how my room actually feels\") or aspiration\n  (\"I want to be the teacher who says it that way\").\n\n============================================================\n4. AUTHOR-ACADEMY AUDIT FILTER (used by the voice critic)\n============================================================\n\nIf the generated Brick is...\n\n  Too \"AI-ish\" (generic, robotic, perfect grammar but no soul)\n    → The voice critic should rewrite it with a personal anecdote or\n      Master Teacher tip in the Hook, vary sentence rhythm, and add at\n      least one tactical-specificity moment.\n\n  Too \"Human-ish\" (messy, no standards alignment, but great story)\n    → Preserve the voice; add the structural alignment.\n\n  A \"Masterwork\" (clear, spiky, actionable, aligned)\n    → Pass through unchanged; flag for featured-Brick promotion.\n";
